## 5. Platoon assignments

Every step in the tick names the model that owns it, with capability + cost + speed justification — per the Platoon Assignment rule. **v1.1 key change:** Rakon promoted from "batched 6h debate-review" to **per-tick astronomer-utility judge** — possible because `warm_models` already pins Rakon resident on Mac Pro 24h, so cold-load tax doesn't apply per-tick. Critically, the **drafter is on Mac Studio and the judge is on Mac Pro** — separate hosts, separate weights, no author-bias.

| Step | Model | Why this model |
|---|---|---|
| 5.1 Pick page & proposal type | Rule-based code (v1); **HwaO (Claude Sonnet)** at v1.1 if a learned policy is wanted | Cheap deterministic routing. Cloud cost only kicks in once we want a learned policy. |
| 5.2 Generate proposal — SectionRewrite / ClaimInsert / HeroFactUpgrade | **AstroSage-70B** (Mac Studio, ~42GB, warm) | Default for any astronomy draft per Roster v2. 86% AstroBench, calibrated for consensus/debate framing. Cost: free. Speed: ~30–90s per ~500-word section. |
| 5.3 Generate proposal — EvidenceLink (paper-finding) | **Atom-Astronomy-7B** (Mac Studio, ~5GB, always warm) | Triages arXiv candidates against the claim text; roster's default for astronomy-specific high-volume scoring. Cost: free. Speed: <5s/candidate. Co-resident with AstroSage-70B (✅ comfortable per roster cheat-sheet). |
| 5.4 Structural score recompute | **Pure Python** (`page_health.py`) | Deterministic guard rail. Cost: 0. Speed: <500ms. The composite metric cannot be 100% model-weighted or it stops being a metric — this is the anchor that lets us trust the judge's swings. |
| 5.5 Quality gate — claim ↔ evidence alignment | **Atom-7B** | Per roster: "astronomy evidence scoring (claim ↔ paper alignment)" is Atom's default lane. Calibrated, fast, free. Threshold 0.55; below → REJECT before the judge wastes cycles. |
| **5.6 Astronomer-utility judge** (the new heart of the metric) | **Rakon** (`deepseek-r1:671b`, Mac Pro, kept warm 24h) | The judge needs the strongest available astronomy + reasoning capacity *and* must be different weights from the drafter to avoid author-bias. Rakon is the only local model that satisfies both. Cost: free (electricity). Speed: ~30s per judge call, ×3 for median = ~90s. Cold-load (minutes) is amortized to zero by `warm_models` keep-alive. |
| 5.7 Judge fallback | **Buddle** (`deepseek-r1:32b`, Mac Pro) | If Rakon is evicted (shouldn't happen given keep-alive, but defensive) or returns a malformed score for >2 of 3 calls. Buddle still has CoT; loses on raw judgment depth but is functional. Logged in `model_judge` field so we can see when fallback fires. |
| 5.8 Rollback decision logic | **Pure Python** | Threshold check on `Δq ≥ 0.02` and structural guards. No LLM needed; deterministic. |
| 5.9 Periodic audit / `program.md` tuning / judge-prompt-version review | **Kun (Claude Opus, cloud)** — weekly | Cross-cutting analysis: are commits actually improving the page? Is the judge calibrated against Papa's manual reads? Does `program.md` need rewriting? Irreplaceable for synthesis judgment; expensive enough to use weekly, not per-tick. |

### 5.1 Why drafter ≠ judge

Without separation, the loop would converge to whatever AstroSage finds aesthetically pleasing about its own drafts. Symptoms would include scoring drift (judge gives same content rising scores over time) and stylistic homogenization. Rakon judges with different weights + different inductive biases + a strict rubric prompt, which neutralizes the author-bias channel. Cost is one extra ~30s judge call per side of the comparison.

### 5.2 Hardware co-residency

Per tick, the active footprint is:

- **Mac Studio:** AstroSage-70B (42GB) + Atom-7B (5GB) + Celery overhead = ~52GB resident on the unified pool. ✅ comfortable per roster cheat-sheet. Blanc must NOT be invoked during a tick (roster hard rule: never two 70B-class on Studio simultaneously).
- **Mac Pro:** Rakon (~404GB resident, exclusive). Buddle MUST be evicted whenever Rakon is loaded — already the case under `warm_models`.

Cross-host: drafting on Studio + judging on Pro is genuine parallelism — Pro's judge call can begin the moment Studio's draft is applied. The 90s judge cost in §2.2 assumes Pro and Studio overlap on different steps.

### 5.3 What we deliberately don't use

- **Blanc** — non-astronomy drafter; would conflict with AstroSage-70B on Studio.
- **Nutty** — too small to judge astronomer-utility credibly.
- **Mima** — general scoring; Atom-7B is better for astronomy alignment.
- **HwaO/Kun as judge** — paid Claude tokens × 3 × 288 ticks/day = budget burn for something a warm Rakon does for free.

